The '''Committee on Data for Science and Technology''' ('''CODATA''') was established in 1966 as an interdisciplinary committee of the [[International Council for Science]]. It seeks to improve the compilation, critical evaluation, storage, and retrieval of data of importance to [[science]] and [[technology]].

The CODATA Task Group on Fundamental Constants was established in 1969. Its purpose is to periodically provide the international scientific and technological communities with an internationally accepted set of values of the [[dimensionless physical constant|fundamental physical constant]]s and closely related [[conversion factor]]s for use worldwide. The first such CODATA set was published in 1973, later in 1986, 1998, 2002 and the fifth in 2006. The latest version is Version 6.0 called "2010CODATA" published on 2 June 2011.

The CODATA recommended values of fundamental physical constants are published at the NIST Reference on Constants, Units, and Uncertainty.<ref name="CODATA">
{{cite web
 |author=CODATA
 |year=2010
 |title=CODATA Recommended Values of the Fundamental Physical Constants: 2010
 |url=http://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Constants/index.html
 |publisher=[[NIST]]
}}</ref>

CODATA sponsors the [http://www.codata.org/archives/conferences.html CODATA international conference] every two years.

